│ Understanding the Issue\n\nThe core problem is a miscompilation in `instcombine` related   │
│ to the `llvm.cttz` intrinsic. The original code uses `cttz(x, is_zero_poison=false)`,      │
│ which has well-defined behavior for `x=0` (it returns the bitwidth). The call is also      │
│ marked `noundef`, guaranteeing it never returns an `undef` or `poison`                     │
│ value.\n\n`instcombine` transforms this to `cttz(x, is_zero_poison=true)`. With            │
│ `is_zero_poison=true`, `cttz(0, ...)` produces a `poison` value. This `poison` value       │
│ violates the `noundef` attribute on the call instruction, leading to undefined behavior.   │
│ The Alive2 verification tool correctly flags this as a refinement failure: the transformed │
│ code is less defined than the source.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log     │
│ shows that `instcombine` performs a series of transformations. The key transformation is   │
│ not immediately obvious from the log, but the final IR shows that `llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %x,   │
│ i1 false)` has been changed to `llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %x, i1 true)`. The log also shows        │
│ `canonicalizeICmpPredicate` being involved, which swaps the `select` operands and inverts  │
│ the predicate. This happens because the `cttz` transform enables it. The crucial change is │
│ the one on the `cttz` call itself.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nBy inspecting the LLVM │
│ source code, specifically `InstCombinerImpl::visitCallInst` in `InstCombineCalls.cpp`, I   │
│ found the logic responsible for this transformation. The code around line 1000 checks if   │
│ the result of a `cttz` or `ctlz` call is only used when the input is non-zero. If so, it   │
│ changes `is_zero_poison` from `false` to `true` to enable further optimizations.\n\nThe    │
│ check is implemented using `isKnownNonZero`. This analysis correctly determines that the   │
│ value of `%ct` is only used when `%x` is non-zero due to the `select` condition `icmp ne   │
│ %x, 0`.\n\nHowever, the transformation logic has a flaw: it does not consider the          │
│ `noundef` attribute on the `CallInst`. While the *result* of the `select` is correct, the  │
│ `cttz` instruction itself is executed unconditionally. When `%x` is 0, the transformed     │
│ `cttz` produces `poison`, which violates the `noundef` contract of the call. This is the   │
│ root cause of the undefined behavior.\n\nThe fix is to prevent this transformation from    │
│ occurring if the call instruction is marked `noundef`. The existing check for              │
│ `isKnownNonZero` is correct in terms of dataflow, but it's insufficient when `noundef` is  │
│ present.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe edit needs to be made in                  │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp` where the `cttz`/`ctlz` intrinsic   │
│ is being transformed. I will add a condition to check for the `noundef` attribute before   │
│ proceeding with the transformation.\n\n```cpp\n//                                          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp:1001\n\n      // If we know that the  │
│ input to cttz/ctlz is non-zero, then we can\n      // replace the is_zero_poison argument  │
│ with true. This allows scalar-to-vector\n      // to recognize the operation, and it can   │
│ be a useful hint for other\n      // transforms.\n      if (!IsZeroPoison &&               │
│ isKnownNonZero(V, DL, 0, &AC, &CI, &DT) &&\n          !CI.hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef))  │
│ {\n        CI.getArgOperandUse(1).set(ConstantInt::getTrue(CI.getContext()));\n            │
│ return &CI;\n      }\n```\n\nI will add `!CI.hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef)` to the        │
│ condition. This ensures that if the call has a `noundef` attribute, we do not change       │
│ `is_zero_poison` to `true`, thus avoiding the miscompilation.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe  │
│ issue is a classic case of a transformation being locally correct from a data-flow         │
│ perspective but globally incorrect due to interaction with an attribute (`noundef`). By    │
│ adding a check for the `noundef` attribute, the transformation is made safe, and the       │
│ miscompilation is resolved. The fix is simple, targeted, and correctly addresses the root  │
│ cause of the problem."})                                                                   │
